On May 29, 2009, the President of the United States made a statement regarding the beginning of negotiations on a Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty. The President emphasized the importance of addressing nuclear proliferation and working towards a nuclear-free world. He welcomed the agreement reached at the Conference on Disarmament to start negotiations on the treaty, which aims to end the production of fissile materials for atomic bombs. The President stated that a verified cut-off treaty is an essential element of his vision for a world without nuclear weapons. He believes that the treaty will help limit nuclear arsenals, strengthen the Non-Proliferation Treaty, and prevent terrorists from accessing nuclear materials. The President expressed satisfaction with the end of a decade of inactivity in the Conference on Disarmament and highlighted the commitment to working together on this global challenge. He pledged to consult and cooperate with the governments involved to complete the treaty as soon as possible.